  "prompt": "What are the legal precedents related to money laundering cases?",
  "response": "There are several important legal precedents related to money laundering cases. Some key examples include:\n\n1. United States v. Bank of New England (1989)\n- Established corporate liability for failing to report suspicious transactions\n- Set important precedent for Bank Secrecy Act enforcement\n\n2. United States v. BCCI (1991)\n- Major international banking money laundering case\n- Highlighted cross-border financial crime challenges\n\n3. Proceeds of Crime Act (UK, 2002)\n- Created comprehensive framework for money laundering prosecution\n- Expanded definitions of financial crimes\n\n4. Basel Committee Guidelines\n- International standards for anti-money laundering compliance\n- Influential in developing global regulatory approaches\n\n5. Bank Secrecy Act (USA)\n- Foundational legislation for detecting and preventing money laundering\n- Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n\nThese cases and regulations have shaped modern approaches to investigating and prosecuting money laundering. They established important legal principles regarding financial transparency, reporting requirements, and corporate accountability.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these specific precedents?",
